WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.460
 So now we're going to talk about how you use JavaScript in a browser and, as I said before,

00:00:04.460 --> 00:00:08.520
 this is just only one of the possible ways that you might use Java.

00:00:08.520 --> 00:00:16.520
 But this is pretty much what we'd call vanilla Java, or basic Java, or Java without Vue, or Java without jQuery, or Java without Node.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:24.720
 This was the original JavaScript purpose, right? It was to be in the browser, augment HTML.

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:30.120
 So here we have a happy little bit of HTML.

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:34.320
 We've got some HTML, you've got a body, you've got a paragraph tag, and we've got this script tag.

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:41.740
 So the script tag says we're moving out of HTML as syntax, and we are then writing some JavaScript code.

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:44.280
 And we are talking to the document.

00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:50.800
 Document, the DOM, is, in a sense, that part of your browser that's like the pixels that you're seeing.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:59.160
 And so this JavaScript code can write to what you're seeing on the screen by going through this const, or this variable called document.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:07.380
 Document.write writes onto the screen, and so if you take a look at this code, it's, it's, um, it's coming down,

00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:12.200
 it's, out comes the title, out comes the body, the paragraph comes out, then it drops into JavaScript,

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:18.360
 and then this little string gets written out, then it goes back in, the no script tag is in case there's no JavaScript,

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:21.740
 which is really rare these days, and then the paragraph comes out.

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:29.440
 So the point is, is that this has created a three-line web page, the first and the third line come from HTML,

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:34.400
 and the second line comes from JavaScript. Not that this is a particularly useful example,

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:42.760
 it just points out that JavaScript has access to the screen when it's running inside of a web page.

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:46.720
 That's powerful, and we're gonna drive a truck through all that.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:51.280
 So whenever I learn a new programming language, the first thing I got to do is print a debug statement.

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:59.120
 And the debug statement is called alert, and you say alert, you put a string in it, and it stops,

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:02.800
 it stops the program, and you have to press OK, then it continues on.

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:06.880
 So that way I'm like, did that code run or not? And I just put a little alert hello world in there,

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:12.800
 and then poof, up it goes, and then just pops up a little dialogue, and you press OK, and it continues.

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:19.040
 So that's really quite nice, and so here's a little example of that where we're cruising along,

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:25.040
 the paragraph is written out, and one of the things that you'll notice is that this alert box

00:02:25.040 --> 00:02:31.200
 actually stops the JavaScript. So we switch into JavaScript, the browser is still parsing the page,

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:37.280
 and you'll see sometimes the little spinner is still spinning. So it stops, it puts up the alert

00:02:37.280 --> 00:02:44.320
 dialogue box, here I am, and waits until you press OK. And in a sense, your browser is paused at that

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:49.280
 point, because literally it doesn't know what you're going to do, and this JavaScript has every right

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:54.880
 to change every bit of this page, because the JavaScript is in the page using a document.

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:01.760
 So it pauses until you press OK, and then it picks back up, and then it will write hello world,

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:07.360
 and the second paragraph will come. But alert, you just stick it in your JavaScript, and whatever's

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:14.640
 happening, bang, it stops right there, and everything stops. And so that's a pretty cool thing,

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:20.240
 and so you can't use it too much, you can't use it in a loop, and if you do it too many times,

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:23.680
 your browser will be like, why is this page throwing up so many alert boxes? But

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:26.480
 in a pinch, it's the simplest thing.

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:34.480
 So there's three ways to get JavaScript into your web page. One is inline in the document,

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:37.920
 and that's what I just showed you, with a da-da-da-da script, da-da-da-da slash script.

00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:43.200
 It can be, we've done, and we've done this before, it's part of an event in an HTML tag.

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:48.880
 I'll show you that. Or you can put the JavaScript in its own little file, usually ending in .js.

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:55.680
 So here's the second one. This is the one where we're putting in an onclick method. And so we've

00:03:55.680 --> 00:04:00.640
 been doing this, right? We've been doing onclick methods, where we'll have an href, and then

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:05.760
 onclick, and then say something. And in this one, this part here in the middle, that is just

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:10.880
 JavaScript, and that's what has semicolons to end each line. White space doesn't matter, this isn't

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:18.800
 Python, don't need new lines, et cetera. So when we click on this click me button, that is going

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:24.800
 to start running this code. Now the page is already fully rendered, and the click me button

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:30.160
 is waiting to be clicked. And onclick, that's when a click happens, event-driven programming,

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:37.120
 then it runs the alert, pauses. Better change the color there. It runs the alert.

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:46.640
 How come I can't get it to be yellow? There it's yellow. Clear it, go back up,

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:53.600
 and be yellow. Thank you for being yellow. So you click on it, it runs this JavaScript,

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:58.720
 which runs the alert, which pops the box up, then you press the OK, and then it continues on this

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:07.440
 code. Now the return false is telling the anchor tag not to follow the link, right? And so that

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:12.480
 basically says, I, the onclick method, have processed this particular click. And so that's

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:20.800
 what the return false does. So we are basically just have JavaScript in the middle of a tag that's

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:28.240
 triggered when an event happens, so event-based programming. The other thing we can do is we can

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:33.840
 make this in a completely separate file. So we're going to have this file called script.js. Now it

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:37.920
 doesn't need a script tag, because it knows that it's JavaScript, so that's just code. This happens

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:43.200
 to be one line that's got a document.writeHelloWorld, and now we embed it with a script tag and a

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:48.160
 slash script, but now we just say source equals script. It pulls it in, it loads and runs and

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:54.160
 parses that whole thing, and as a side effect, it writes out, you know, one paragraph, hello world,

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:59.520
 and the second paragraph. And of course, usually this isn't doing work. Usually this is defining

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:05.120
 a bunch of functions that we're going to use later, and so usually this is script.js is a function,

00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:09.760
 function, function, function, so we're kind of loading a library of functions that we're going

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:15.040
 to use later, but I just put this document right so you can kind of see when it's happening as the

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:22.720
 document is loading. So in any programming language, we can make errors as a programmer,

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:30.640
 right? We can make syntax errors. The problem is when you're looking at a webpage, and in that

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:37.760
 webpage there's a JavaScript syntax error, they decided a long time ago not to bother the poor

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:43.120
 user with a JavaScript syntax error, because really the person, unless you're writing it in

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:50.400
 the first place, the person looking at the screen of, you know, amazon.com or drchuck.com,

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:55.840
 if I got a syntax error in drchuck.com, why tell you that there's a syntax error?

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:02.480
 So what it actually does is it just like, well, I guess I'll stop running the JavaScript because

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:06.320
 it's got a problem, but I'm not going to tell the user, which means my page is broken and I don't

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:14.000
 even know that. So it stops, and so syntax errors happen, and it just stops the execution. So let's

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.840
 take a look at a little example here, a little example where we have two chunks of JavaScript.

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:26.000
 We come in, we got the first one, and this first one has a syntax error, okay? And that means the

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:32.240
 alert's not going to work. Now what happens is, is it in effect ignores everything after that point.

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:36.080
 If it's executing through a script file, it might be defining a bunch of functions. If it finds a

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:41.200
 syntax error a third of the way through, the other two-thirds don't matter because it has stopped

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:46.640
 parsing that file until the end of the script tag. And then when it sees a new script tag,

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:52.400
 hope springs eternal, and it starts parsing it again. And so that's why when this page runs,

00:07:52.400 --> 00:08:01.920
 when this page runs, you see first paragraph, this goes, blows up, which means it skips down to here,

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:07.360
 then you see two paragraph come out, and then you see the alert second time. You never see any of

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:14.400
 these alerts because that error is on the first line of the JavaScript, which invalidates the

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:21.120
 rest of the JavaScript, but until another script tag. And sometimes what you're doing, you're like

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:24.240
 including one library, another library, and another library, and another library.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:28.880
 If you have a syntax error in that library that you're including, most of that library won't

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:35.040
 actually be activated, right? But it doesn't mean if you have like five libraries that you're

00:08:35.040 --> 00:08:38.880
 loading with five script tags, just because the first library has a syntax error, it can still

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:45.680
 load the other four libraries. But it's just, it pumps. There could be hundreds of lines of code

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:51.680
 here, and it all is for naught because it saw a syntax error and ignored the rest of it up to the

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:59.440
 end of that script tag. Now, the end user can't see the error, so when you're doing software

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:03.840
 development, you've got to put in extra effort because when you're like writing code and hitting

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:08.960
 refresh, writing code and hitting refresh, well, yeah, that's the user hitting the refresh in the

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:14.160
 browser, but if you're writing JavaScript, you want to see what's wrong. And so we have places

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:18.800
 that we have to look to see if there are actually JavaScript errors in our code. And once we start

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:23.680
 developing JavaScript, I assure you that there will be errors in your code. There's always errors

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:31.840
 in my code. And so all of these situations, whether it be browsers, Firefox, Chrome, Safari,

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:37.120
 they all have some kind of a web developer console that you unlock. And then you can go, there's

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:42.320
 always one of these tabs that says console, and console is all the error messages that are coming

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:48.320
 out. And so if you made that same bit of code and you had the console turned on, you would see a

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:54.160
 happy little error that says syntax error on line three of that file. I mean, it would just run the

00:09:54.160 --> 00:10:00.400
 okays later in the file, but it will tell us that. So you'll find that once you start developing

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:06.400
 JavaScript, you're making a big mistake if you don't have this little developer console open

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.760
 almost all the time, at least to the JavaScript console, because that's how you debug your

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:17.200
 JavaScript. It'll literally just like silently, you're like, hmm, I changed something and nothing

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:21.120
 happened. I changed something and nothing happened. I'm going crazy. Well, look at the console.

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:25.920
 You changed something, but there was a syntax error above it. And so it didn't matter what you said

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:30.960
 after that. It really ignores everything after that. So that's why it's so important to have the

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:36.560
 debugger console doing all the time. Thankfully, all modern browsers have a good debugger console.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:41.200
 In the old days, Firefox was the only one that had a thing called firebug, which was this console,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:46.080
 which had to install it and add it. And it's a person wrote it as an open source project.

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:51.200
 And it got so popular that people just put it into the browsers rather than making you install it.

00:10:51.200 --> 00:11:00.080
 So it was pretty cool. So back to debugging, there is a function called console.log and it

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:05.760
 allows you to log variables and strings and whatever. And unlike the alert, it just shows

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:12.560
 up in that console. So you can put it inside of a loop. You don't have to press okay. It doesn't

